column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30 A.M. ON AUGUST 12, 1986, A ROLLINS LEASE TRUCK, DRIV EN BY WILLIAM ORTEGA FOR RINCHEM CO., INC. MADE A LEFT TURN FROM LEE TREVIN O TO PELLICAON IN EL PASO, TX. DURING THIS TURN, THE DOOR OF THE VAN TRUCK CAME OPEN AND TWO (2) DRUMS OF III TRICHLOROETHANE FELL FROM THE REAR OF TH E TRUCK. ONE (1) OF THE DRUMS RUPTURED AT THE BOTTOM AND SPILLED OUT APPROX . FIFTY (50) GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE STREET. THE OTHER DRUM HAD A SEAM TH AT WAS SEEPING, BUT NO SIGNIFICANTLY. THE DRUM THAT WAS NOT BROKEN WAS PUT INTO AN OVERPAK AND CONTAINED. THE III TRICHLOROETHANE ON THE STREET WAS AB SORBED BY SAND AND PUT INTO TEN (10) OPEN HEAD DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. RINCHEM CO., INC. BEING A HAZARDOUS WASTE TRANSPORTER, REMOVED THE SPILL MATERIAL A ND SENT SAMPLES AND PROFILES TO U.S. POLLUTION CONTROL, INC. THE MATERIAL W ILL BE DISPOSED OF UPON APPROVAL BY THE TSD FACILITY AT GRASSY MOUNTAIN, UT AH. THE RINCHEM CO., INC. DRIVER WAS CITED FOR FAILURE TO SECURE HIS LOAD. THE EL PASO FIRE DEPT.'S SUPPLEMENTAL INCIDENT REPORT #17541 LISTED SEVEN ( 7) INDIVIDUALS AS HAVING BEEN CHECKED OR TREATED FOR VAPOR INHALATION. ALL ARE BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED IMMEDIATELY. BOTH RINCHEM CO., INC. AND ROLLINS TRUCK LEASING ARE INSURED BY THE CONTINENTAL INSURANCE CO. LES HUSS OF CRAWFORD AND COMPANY, 4100 RIO BRAVO, SUITE 215, EL PASO, TX 79902 WAS APPOINTED BY CONTINENTAL AS INS. ADJUSTER FOR RELATED CLAIMS. (915-533-9801 ).

column168: DOCK MAN DISCOVERED DAMAGED CARTON WHILE HE WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  THE CARTON WAS FOUND LYING ON ITS SIDE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  TOPS WERE FOUND TO BE LOOSE ON TWO OF THE PLASTIC JUGS WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO ESCAPE AS THE JUGS WERE LYING ON THEIR SIDES.  CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS & D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. column168: RADIACTIVE AIR FREIGHT SHIPMENT BEING TRANSPORTED IN A BAGGAGE CART ROLLED FROM THE CART TO THE PAVEMENT BREAKING THE PLASTIC OUTER SHELL AWAY FROM TH E INNER METAL CONTAINER.  THIS WAS CAUSED 1. BY THE OBJECT BEING OF A ROUND NATURE ALLOWING IT TO ROLL. 2. THE CURTAINS IN THE BAGGAGE CART WERE NOT A BLE TO BE CLOSED COMPLETELY DUE TO MECHANICAL MALFUNCTION.  AFTER REALIZING THAT A RADIOACTIVE SHIPMENT WAS INVOLVED, THE ST. LOUIS AIRPORT FIRE DEPAR TMENT AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS WERE CALLED FOR.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND THEY ADVISED TO CALL THE ATOMIC ENERGY AFFICE IN OAK RIDGE, TENN. WITH THE INFOR MATION PROVIDED ON THE AIR WAYBILL, IT WAS ADVISED THAT A 10 FOOT CLEARANCE WOULD BE SUFFICIENT.  THAT GATE AREA AND THE ADJOINING DOWNWIND GATE AREA WERE CLOSED AND EVACUATED. RDIOLOGICAL EMERGENCY PLANNER WAS NOTIFIED. THEY ADVISED TO HAVE A GEIGER COUNTER READING BEFORE MOVING THE SHIPMENT OR CLE ARING THE AREA. A ROBERT HORNSBY OF THE ST. LOUIS COUNTY OFFICE OF CIVIL PR EPAREDNESS ARRIVED AND WITH THE AID OF A COUNTER, RENDERED THE AREA AND ALL INDIVIDUALS INVOLVED TO BE SAFE AND THAT THERE HAD NOT BEEN A LEAKAGE.  BA GGAGE CART WILL BE TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE FOR REPAIR.  OBJECTS OF THIS NATURE SHOULD BE PACKAGED IN A MANNER THA WOULD LIMIT THE POSSIBILITY OF ROLLING IN SUCH AN EASY MANNER.  A CRATING WOULD BE SUGGESTED.
